To add comments to your Docusaurus blog, I recommend using Giscus, a system that leverages GitHub Discussions. It's a great fit since your portfolio is already hosted on GitHub.

Here‚Äôs a summary of the steps to integrate Giscus into your Docusaurus site:

### 1. Enable GitHub Discussions

First, you need to enable GitHub Discussions for the repository where you want to store the comments.

1.  Go to your repository's **Settings** page.
2.  In the **Features** section, click on **Set up discussions**.
3.  Follow the prompts to enable discussions.

### 2. Install and Configure Giscus

Next, you'll need to install the Giscus GitHub App and configure it for your repository.

1.  Go to the [Giscus website](https://giscus.app/) and click on the **"Add Giscus to your repository"** button.
2.  Select the repository where you enabled discussions.
3.  Configure the Giscus settings, such as the discussion category where comments will be created.

### 3. Get Repository and Category IDs

You'll need to get the repository ID and the discussion category ID using the GitHub GraphQL API.

1.  Go to the [GitHub GraphQL API Explorer](https://docs.github.com/en/graphql/overview/explorer).
2.  Use the following query, replacing `owner` and `name` with your GitHub username and repository name:

```graphql
query {
  repository(owner: "austenstone", name: "portfolio") {
    id
    discussionCategories(first: 10) {
      edges {
        node {
          id
          name
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

3.  From the response, note the `id` of your repository and the `id` of the discussion category you want to use for comments.

### 4. Create a Giscus Component

Now, create a new React component in your Docusaurus project to render the Giscus comments.

1.  Install the `@giscus/react` package:

```bash
npm install @giscus/react
```

2.  Create a new file at `src/components/GiscusComponent/index.tsx` with the following content. Make sure to replace the placeholder values with your actual repository and category IDs.

```tsx
import React from 'react';
import Giscus from "@giscus/react";
import { useColorMode } from '@docusaurus/theme-common';

export default function GiscusComponent() {
  const { colorMode } = useColorMode();

  return (
    <Giscus
      repo="austenstone/portfolio"
      repoId="YOUR_REPOSITORY_ID" // Replace with your repository ID
      category="Announcements"
      categoryId="YOUR_CATEGORY_ID" // Replace with your category ID
      mapping="url"
      strict="0"
      reactionsEnabled="1"
      emitMetadata="1"
      inputPosition="top"
      theme={colorMode}
      lang="en"
      loading="lazy"
      crossorigin="anonymous"
      async
    />
  );
}
```

### 5. Swizzle the `BlogPostItem` Component

To display the comments on your blog posts, you need to "swizzle" the `BlogPostItem` component. This allows you to customize it.

1.  Run the following command in your terminal:

```bash
npm run swizzle @docusaurus/theme-classic BlogPostItem -- --wrap
```

2.  This will create a new file at `src/theme/BlogPostItem/index.js`. Open this file and replace its content with the following:

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import { useBlogPost } from '@docusaurus/theme-common/internal'
import BlogPostItem from '@theme-original/BlogPostItem';
import GiscusComponent from '@site/src/components/GiscusComponent';
import useIsBrowser from '@docusaurus/useIsBrowser';

export default function BlogPostItemWrapper(props) {
  const { metadata, isBlogPostPage } = useBlogPost()
  const isBrowser = useIsBrowser();

  const { frontMatter } = metadata
  const { enableComments } = frontMatter

  return (
    <>
      <BlogPostItem {...props} />
      {(enableComments && isBlogPostPage) && (
        <GiscusComponent />
      )}
    </>
  );
}
```

### 6. Enable Comments in Your Blog Posts

Finally, to enable comments on a specific blog post, add `enableComments: true` to the front matter of the Markdown file.

